<P>
Fifteen South Pacific nations alarmed at the depletion of tuna stocks by 
drift-net fishing asked help to force Japan and Taiwan to end the practice. The 
Pacific leaders, meeting in Tarawa, Kiribati, for their two-day annual South 
Pacific forum, are alarmed that the practice -- also called gill-net fishing -- 
threatens the Pacific's economic future, said Cook Islands Prime Minister 
Geoffrey Henry. The technique uses nets up to 30 miles long and has been 
likened to strip mining the ocean. 
