<P>
Japan's leaders agreed to provisionally budget for hefty increases in defense 
spending and overseas aid for the next fiscal year, government officials said. 
They said defense outlays will increase as much as 6.35% in the year that 
begins April 1, 1990, and overseas aid by up to 9.4% over the current fiscal 
year. Japan has been under pressure from the United States to recycle some of 
its huge trade surplus back to the Third World by increasing its spending on 
overseas aid, and this year Japan passed the United States in total overseas 
aid expenditures. Washington has also been pressing Tokyo to take up a greater 
share of the burden of defending itself. 
