<P>
BID FOR PRIME COMPUTER EXTENDED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Minicomputer maker MAI Basic Four Inc. of Tustin said today that it has 
extended its hostile $1.2-billion tender offer for Prime Computer. 
</P>
<P>
MAI Basic Four's cash offer of $19.50 a share has been extended until midnight 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
Prime, based in Natick, Mass., has been fighting off MAI Basic Four's offers 
for the last nine months. On June 23, it agreed to a $1.4-billion merger with 
DR Holdings Inc., a company organized by J. H. Whitney. The deal called for a 
$21.50-a-share cash tender offer for 79% of Prime, with shares not purchased 
converted into $22 principal in 15.5% senior subordinated debt due 2001. 
</P>
<P>
MAI Basic Four, which had initially offered $20 a share, has said it will 
increase its bid but has not done so since the merger deal was announced. 
</P>
